   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1816_08_14_page01.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, remove this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworth's Town</placeName>
                  <date when="1816-08-14">Aug<hi rend="superscript">st</hi> 14<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1816</date></dateline>
              
            </opener>
            <p>
               My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LansL1">Lady Lansdowne</persName>
               <hi rend="underline">Can</hi> you think of me when
               you are so far away? - Yes
               I must believe that you
               <hi rend="underline">can</hi> since you were so <choice><orig>incre<lb/>dibly</orig><reg>incredibly</reg></choice>
               kind as to write to
               me the very day before you
               left <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName> - I assure you
               that if you had not written
               I never should have <choice><orig>sus-<lb/>pected</orig><reg>suspected</reg></choice>
               you of neglecting
               either my father or myself
               so firm is my opinion of
               the constancy of your <choice><orig>re-<lb/>gard</orig><reg>regard</reg></choice>
               for those whom you
               have once honored with
               any portion of your great esteem.
            </p>
            <p>
               I regret that letter of yours
               which is lying at the dead
               letter office at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Canterbury_ENK">Canterbury</placeName>
               <note place="top">119</note>
               
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1816_08_14_page02.jpg"/>
               I rather think that one of
               mine has not reached you
               but I cannot recollect any
               thing it contained except
               a translation of some French
               lines of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BerqA1">Arnauds</persName> <hi rend="underline">on a leaf</hi>
               which my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">father</persName> sent.
            </p>
            <p>
               This note probably will
               find you at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Geneva_SZ">Geneva</placeName>. I hope
               you will have the goodness
               to remember us <choice><orig>affectionate<lb/>=ly</orig><reg>affectionately</reg></choice>
               to our friends there -
               especially to excellent <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DumoE1">M. <lb/>Dumont</persName>
               . - tho he has been
               very naughty about writing
               - not one letter have we
               received from him since
               he went to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Geneva_SZ">Geneva</placeName> - Is he so
               taken up in making <add>new</add> <choice><orig>consti<lb/>-tutions</orig><reg>constitutions</reg></choice>
               that he cannot write
               a letter to his old friends ? -
            </p>
            <p>
               - But I have no right to reproach
               my friends much for not
               writing as I am so very <hi rend="underline">lazy</hi>
               myself - I enclose a <hi rend="underline">notice</hi>
               
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1816_08_14_page03.jpg"/>
               which I wrote <del>for</del> as a tribute
               of regard to my friend <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HamiE1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>.<lb/>Elizabeth Hamilton</persName>
               whose
               death probably you have
               seen in the papers - I <choice><orig>remem<lb/>ber</orig><reg>remember</reg></choice>
               10 or 12 years ago M.
               [unclear]Pictet[/unclear] gave a very good ac
               count in his journal Bri ..
               =tannique of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HamiE1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Hamilton's</persName>
               letters on Education - Per,,
               haps he may now like
               to see this <hi rend="underline">notice</hi> &amp; I hope he
               will take some means
               of doing justice to her <choice><orig>me<lb/>-mory</orig><reg>memory</reg></choice>
               either in the French
               papers or journals - <del><unclear>Does</unclear></del>
               Is the Journal Britannique
               still continued ? -
            </p>
            <p>
               I hope my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LansL1">Lady<lb/> Lansdowne</persName>
               you will do
               me the favor to write and
               tell me <del>the</del> how you like
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#SZ">Switzerland</placeName> - &amp; <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IT">Italy</placeName> -
               I hope you will not see <hi rend="underline">all</hi>
               the churches &amp; palaces which
               
              <note place="top">120</note>
               
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Geneve_33_2_1816_08_14_page04.jpg"/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EustJ1">Eustace</persName> describes - Half of them
               I think would be quite enough
               for me - That <title ref="./Workography.xml#Class1">book</title> gave me
               an indigestion a surfeit of
               churches &amp; palaces - And I
               thought I never should have
               got alive out of the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Vatican-City_IT">Vatican</placeName>
               I was so tired of it - Nevertheless
               I acknowledge that many parts
               of the book are very eloquent -
               - But there is too much of every
               thing - &amp; especially too much <hi rend="underline">fine</hi>
               <hi rend="underline">writing</hi> -
            </p>
            <p>
               I think Lord &amp; Lady Byron's <choice><orig>af-<lb/>fair</orig><reg>affair</reg></choice>
               was all settled before
               you left <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName> &amp; that he
               had gone off with the <choice><orig>univer<lb/>sal</orig><reg>universal</reg></choice>
               execration of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName>.
            </p>
            <p>
               - Perhaps you will meet
               him again in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#SZ"><choice><orig>Swisserland</orig><reg>Switzerland</reg></choice></placeName>
               I hear he is now at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Geneva_SZ">Geneva</placeName>
            </p>
            <p>
               - How <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StaeA1">Madame de Stael</persName> &amp; he
               will talk - I wish I could hear
               them provided I could be
               now &amp; then relieved &amp; refresh
               ed with a little common-
               sense from you &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LansH1">Lord Lans-<lb/>downe</persName>
               - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LambC1">Lady Caroline Lamb</persName>
               has just published a <title ref="./Workography.xml#Glena1">book</title> in
               which there is not one grain
               of common sense &amp; no [unclear]pretine[/unclear]
               
            </p>
            <p>
               <!--More body paragraphs as needed.--></p>
            <p>
